div.p:
Here he tells the World, as well as God, that he hath a Righteous Judgment, a Righteous Understanding, and a Righteous Zeal; yea, a Christian Spirit and Patience, and he goes on, without any confession of Sin, or any thing of that nature; no, that's below him: It is enough for such Men as Isaiah, Job, Daniel, David, John the Evangelist, and Paul the Apostle, and other Apostles, Prophets, and Martyrs, to make such Addresses, and not for such high grown Pharisees as the Quakers; who

 say, they know who are Saints, who are Devils, and who are Apostates, without speaking ever a word; and that they are furnished at all times, on all occasions, and in all cases, with discerning and judgment: Insomuch, that they need no Man to give them discerning, or to inform their Judgments; for they pretend always to be ready furnished, see their Book, Judas and the Jews, &c. p. 58. Where they teach this Doctrine, suitable to Whitehead's Prayer; who therein say, in his own Commendation, that he hath a Righteous Judgment, a Righteous Understanding, a Righteous Zeal; and the like may be said of the Prayers of Stephen Crisp, Richard Ashly, W. Bingly, and others, whose Papers are Printed at the end of their Sermons. In a word, your laying aside the Lord's Prayer, the Ten Commandments, the Apostles Creed, and the like Christian Practices; not only wholly in your Meetings for Worship, but generally in private Families; is a proof, that you are not the Church of the First Born. And to perform my Task, in the second part proposed; I shall transcribe the Cage formerly made, and I hope they will not only see themselves thereby, not be the Church of the First Born; but be humbled, and not think themselves all perfect; also when they consider, that they call the Church of England a Cage of Unclean Birds. They will not be angry with me, for I shall lay Perfection, and Imperfection together, the Pharisees, and the Publicans, heaps upon heaps;

 and if they cannot see themselves to be such; if they desire it, I shall give them a Key to open the Cage, where they may see their greatest Writers, and chief Speakers, guilty of such Crimes, as the Heathen would be ashamed of. I remember how George Fox, use to Preach the Church of England, to be the Cage of Unclean Birds; saying, their Note was no perfection here: And now let them see what perfection there is in the Cage, wherein I have put them; and so I shall conclude this Chapter.

p.q:
My Master is a High and Mighty, and Powerful Prince, and very Honourable;

 Fear and Subjection belongs to him alone: Something you may and ought to do; but if to make the Whore the false Church more Naked, and to scourge her more than some others have done: And indeed my Lord requires something more of you to do, than others before you could do; and tho some of you, present Rulers, be looked upon as great Traitors and Tyrants (in cutting off the King's Head, and extirpating Episcopacy) the Lord doth not account as Men; these things must needs have come to pass for the furtherance of the Kingdom of Jesus Christ, and if you were but faithful to what the Lord requires of you, what you have done to them (in the Murther aforesaid) should not be reckoned an account against you, neither by God nor good Men. Let all forced maintenance to Ministers, as Tythes, be speedily taken away; and let just Men, and righteous Men, and meek Men (i. e. Quakers) have the Power and judgment committed to them, to determin things between Man and Man; down with all that judge for Rewards, and away with all hireling Rulers that execute the Law for Money; and as for the Men call'd Ministers, the way of their setting up, sending forth, and maintenance, are the greatest oppression in the Nation; they are the woful cause of the Nations groaning, their iniquities cry for vengeance, for they are full, they are full, and God's Eternal vengeance is their next Reward from the Eternal God:

 What shall I say of them but this? The Earth is oppressed by them, the Inhabitants groan under them, and God is vexed thro' them, and they are the Men of high Indignation and fierce Wrath; let this Ministry alone, and joyn not your selves to Baal least you perish; neither take part with Antichrist any longer; uphold not this Ministry against my Lord, and this is from the mouth of my Lord to you.

div.p:
Having proceeded thus far in this old controversy, it will not be amiss to let the World see how Sam. Cater's case was manag'd. First by partial Judges, as abovetold; and next by lying Lawyers: For, Tho. Rudyard, S. Cater's Lawyer, thus said in his defence, about the 15 l. I suffered for Sam. Cater as aforesaid, viz.
                     The Fine of 15 l. was paid in Money voluntarily, before distress was made, which is a payment that our Testimony was ever against; and has been oftentimes 3 or 4 times the value of the thing demanded, and charge;

 because they could neither pay, nor compound for such spoiling their Goods, &c.
